# Rust Safety & Unsafe

`unsafe` is a contract with the compiler, not a performance switch. The cost of getting it wrong is undefined behaviour.

## Rules for `unsafe`

- Every `unsafe` block must have a comment explaining the invariant that makes it sound:
  ```rust
  // SAFETY: `ptr` is non-null and aligned because it was obtained from
  // `Box::into_raw` and we hold the only reference.
  unsafe { ptr.as_ref().unwrap_unchecked() }
  ```
- Minimise the scope of `unsafe` blocks — never put more code in `unsafe` than is strictly necessary
- Never use `unsafe` to silence a borrow checker error — that error means the code has a real bug
- Encapsulate all `unsafe` in a safe abstraction with a well-defined public API; do not expose raw pointers or raw indices across module boundaries
- Run `cargo miri` in CI to catch UB that the compiler itself misses (dangling pointers, uninitialized reads, invalid data)

## Common sources of UB to avoid

- Casting `&T` to `&mut T` via pointer casts — this is instant UB if any shared reference exists
- Creating two mutable references to the same memory — violates the aliasing model
- Reading uninitialised memory — use `MaybeUninit<T>` if you must construct values before initialising
- Transmuting between types with different sizes or alignment requirements
- Calling a function through a function pointer of the wrong type

## `unsafe` traits

- Implementing `Send` or `Sync` manually is an `unsafe impl` — only do this when you have formally verified the type is safe to cross thread boundaries
- Document every `unsafe impl` with the reasoning

## Input validation & injection

- Never pass user-controlled strings to shell commands — use `std::process::Command` with argument arrays, never `sh -c`
- Validate all external input at system boundaries (network, files, environment variables) before passing into business logic
- Never deserialise untrusted `bincode`/`postcard`/raw bytes directly into types that contain pointers or `unsafe` invariants

## Secrets & credentials

- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, or tokens in source — load from environment variables or a secrets manager
- Zero sensitive memory before dropping: use the `zeroize` crate (`Zeroize` + `ZeroizeOnDrop`) for key material
- Use `secrecy::Secret<T>` to prevent accidental `Debug` printing of sensitive values

## Cryptography

- Never implement cryptographic primitives — use `ring`, `rustls`, or `RustCrypto` crates
- Use `ring::rand::SystemRandom` / `getrandom` for cryptographically secure random numbers — not `rand::thread_rng()` for security-sensitive purposes
- Hash passwords with `argon2` (crate) — never SHA-1, MD5, or plain SHA-256 for passwords

## Dependency hygiene

- Audit dependencies with `cargo audit` in CI — subscribe to `RustSec` advisories
- Pin dependencies with `Cargo.lock` (always commit it for binaries; do not commit for libraries)
- Minimise `unsafe` in dependencies — use `cargo geiger` to surface unsafe counts in the dependency tree
